BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Creative Writing Series: Maria Kuznetsova\, Fiction
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260408T233000Z
DTEND;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260409T003000Z
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_51534087526177
DESCRIPTION:Please join us for the next event in the 2025-2026 Creative Wr
 iting Series: a reading and Q&A featuring novelist Maria Kuznetsova! This 
 event is free and open to all\, and will be available in person and livest
 reamed. Maria Kuznetsova was born in Kyiv\, Ukraine\, and moved to the Uni
 ted States as a child. She is the author of the novels Oksana\, Behave! an
 d Something Unbelievable. An alum of the UC Davis master’s program in cr
 eative writing\, she now lives in Auburn\, Alabama\, with her family\, whe
 re she is an associate professor of creative writing at Auburn University.
  She is also the fiction editor of the Southern Humanities Review and her 
 work appears or is forthcoming in dozens of literary journals including On
 e Story\, The Yale Review\, Southern Review\, Threepenny Review\, and The 
 Sun. The Creative Writing Series is presented by the UC Davis Department o
 f English\, Creative Writing Master of Fine Arts Program\, and the UC Davi
 s Library. The views expressed in this series\, including descriptions and
  biographies\, are those of the speakers and not meant to represent the vi
 ews of any other person or institution.
LOCATION:Shields Library\, 205
URL:https://events.library.ucdavis.edu/event/creative-writing-series-maria
 -kuznetsova-novelist
X-SOURCE:UC Davis Library
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Publish Your Work: From Idea to Impact — Traditional and Alterna
 tive Options
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260409T200000Z
DTEND;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260409T210000Z
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_52322769236438
DESCRIPTION:Publish Your Work: From Idea to Impact\, Traditional and Alter
 native Options is a Zoom workshop that will give you an overview of (1) tr
 aditional publishing options\, such as peer-reviewed journals\, and (2) al
 ternative publishing options\, such as preprints\, open methods\, and open
  data. Whether you’re going to be publishing for the first time or you
 ’ve published many times in the past\, join us to learn more about open 
 research\, avoiding predatory publishers\, selecting an appropriate journa
 l\, and how to publish your research outputs in ways that go beyond the tr
 aditional journal article. No previous experience is required. All discipl
 ines are welcome. Please register for the Zoom link. This six-workshop ser
 ies is a collaboration between the library's Scholarly Communications Prog
 ram\, the Researcher Services department\, and Blaisdell Medical Library. 
 For any questions\, please contact the Scholarly Communication Officer Mic
 hael Ladisch (mladisch@ucdavis.edu). Check our events calendar for more pu
 blishing workshops.
URL:https://events.library.ucdavis.edu/event/workshop-publish-your-work
X-SOURCE:UC Davis Library
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:AI Literacy & Logic: 1-day intensive course
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260410T160000Z
DTEND;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260410T233000Z
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_52340792785132
DESCRIPTION:A 198 course for College of Letters & Science majors. The land
 scape of the academic and professional world is shifting. Whether you are 
 an aspiring historian\, a budding chemist\, or a future sociologist\, AI i
 s no longer a "tech" skill—it’s a foundational literacy. Developed thr
 ough a collaboration between the UC Davis College of Letters & Science and
  DataLab\, this 1-unit intensive course is designed to unveil Artificial I
 ntelligence. We’ve stripped away the dense math and complex coding to gi
 ve you a conceptual\, high-level understanding of how artificial intellige
 nce systems work\, why they matter\, and how to make them work for you. Wh
 y Enroll? In a single day\, you will move from being a passive AI user to 
 a critical\, strategic collaborator. This training is specifically curated
  for L&S students to ensure you graduate with the competitive edge needed 
 for the rapidly evolving\, AI-driven workplace. No technical background? N
 o problem. This course has no prerequisites. It is designed for thinkers\,
  writers\, and researchers across all liberal arts and science disciplines
 . The curriculum is divided into four deep-dive modules: How AI Thinks Und
 erstand the "brain" of the machine. We’ll explore the theories of langua
 ge and cognition that allow Large Language Models (LLMs) to function\, and
  provide a framework for evaluating their potential and limits. How to Use
  AI Responsibly AI isn't a magic wand—it’s a tool with a history and c
 onsequences. We discuss the environmental and societal impacts\, how to en
 sure the veracity of AI results\, and why reproducibility is the cornersto
 ne of ethical tech. How to Talk with AI Master the art and science of prom
 pt engineering. Learn what happens behind the scenes when you send a promp
 t. Develop sophisticated strategies to get the exact results you need. Mod
 ule 4: How AI Talks with You A look at the future of AI implementation. Fr
 om simple chatbots to complex autonomous "Agents\," learn how AI is being 
 embedded into systems and how to evaluate its activity. By the end of this
  one-day course\, you will be able to: Define "AI" and distinguish it from
  traditional statistics and data science. Identify whether a real-world pr
 oblem is suitable for an AI solution. Develop advanced prompting strategie
 s that produce reliable\, useful results. Critically interrogate your own 
 engagement with AI and its impact on our society and environment. Register
  Now This intensive\, one-day course will be offered five times during the
  Spring Quarter 2026. You only need to register for one date. Time: 9:00 A
 M – 4:30 PM (with a break for lunch) Credits: 1 Unit CRN: TBA Eligibilit
 y: Open to all students with a major in the College of Letters & Science. 
 Priority: Registration priority is given to Seniors (4th years) and studen
 ts graduating in Spring or Summer 2026. Other students in the College are 
 encouraged to enroll and will be admitted as space permits.
URL:https://events.library.ucdavis.edu/event/ai-literacy-logic-spring-2026
X-SOURCE:UC Davis Library
END:VEVENT
